icult to learn and play well?  Not just solo, but in groups, from level 1 to 60.<br>
<br>
My vote is of course, the Bard.<br>
<br>
Twisting isnt really that hard, but it does take a while to get used to.  Whats hard about Bards is song selection.  Most other caster type classes get upgrades to lines of spells that make for relatively simple spell selection.  Their roles are pretty well defined for most mobs on raids and in groups.  Bards, on the other hand, are different.  <br>
Lets say a Bard is in a 46+ Raid type situation:<br>
The Bard can can sing resists and mana.<br>
The Bard can sing melee haste and buffs.  <br>
The Bard can can sing ac/ds/regen.  <br>
The Bard can can sing Debuffs/Dots.<br>
The Bard can be backup chanter and Mez/Charm adds.<br>
Or, what everyone loves to see on those long fights....<br>
The Bard can sing the Food Song!!  woot<br>
And does the Bard do this while meleeing, or does he/she think the extra bonus from weilding instruments is more important?  ( I have epic, and I get a lot more benefits from most songs using the instruments I have.  Proc is nice, d/d is nice, melee damage is nice, but sometimes you want the extra mana/healt regen you get using a lute, or the extra damage/debuff using a good drum)<br>
<br>
Song selection depends on group you are with and Mob you are figthing.  No other class's role in a group depends so much on the environment.<br>
<br>
Bards have many options to solo with as well as they get higher (Fear kite, Dot Kite, Charm Kite)<br>
<br>
A crappy bard is a manasink and a useless spot in a group.  Our melee damage is pitiful, and our debuffs/slows/snares/charms/mezzes are second to every other class that has them.<br>
<br>
Knowing what songs to twist is the biggest challenge of being a Bard, I dont think any other class has such a hard time being used to thier full capacity<br>
